00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:51.430
It's very thin, but it's
two-- I mean, come on.

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:53.030
Who's slightly boggled by that?

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:54.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:56.260
Every single cell
in your body-- you

00:07:56.260 --> 00:07:58.970
have enough DNA in your
body to go to the moon

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:00.460
and back 1,500 times.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:03.590
I find this staggering.

00:08:03.590 --> 00:08:05.770
More people-- I mean,
I'm a biologist.

00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:08.130
I find this stuff cool.

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:12.270
Within that, you have three
billion letters of data,

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:16.500
effectively, of the A's, C's,
T's, and G's, the instructions.

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:18.580
It's a huge amount of data.

00:08:18.580 --> 00:08:20.390
And within that are
the instructions,

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:23.890
the genes, that tell
your cells what to do.

00:08:23.890 --> 00:08:26.236
So how many have we got?

00:08:26.236 --> 00:08:27.860
Well, it was originally
thought that we

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:31.651
had something upwards of
100,000 genes to make a human.

00:08:31.651 --> 00:08:34.150
God, we're probably going to
need a lot of genes, aren't we?

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:36.010
Because we're kind of cool.

00:08:36.010 --> 00:08:38.214
Turns out we've got
about 20,000 genes.

00:08:38.214 --> 00:08:42.450
We're clocking in somewhere
around fruit flies and nematode

00:08:42.450 --> 00:08:44.517
worms.

00:08:44.517 --> 00:08:46.100
So this was a bit
of a shock when they

00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:47.250
sequenced the human genome.

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:49.001
They were like, wha?

00:08:49.001 --> 00:08:50.000
Where are all the genes?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:50.740
They did a bet.

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:53.430
They actually did a
sweepstake to make people

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:55.400
bet on how many genes
there were going to be.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:59.425
And people started out,
like, 150,000, 100,000.

00:08:59.425 --> 00:09:02.430
We were like, whew.

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:05.520
We basically don't really
have that many genes.

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:08.434
We use the ones we have in
very interesting ways, which

00:09:08.434 --> 00:09:10.100
sort of proves it's
not what you've got,

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:11.930
it's what you do
with it that counts.

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:15.670
But we only have
20,000 genes or so.

00:09:15.670 --> 00:09:19.690
And all of that makes you, you.

00:09:19.690 --> 00:09:23.540
And in fact, the sum total
of your-- all your genome,

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:26.090
those phone books
full of information

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:32.270
that is actual genes is
really not very much.

00:09:32.270 --> 00:09:35.170
I told you I really
wasn't very good at this.

00:09:35.170 --> 00:09:41.930
Only about 2% of your genome
