00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:51.280
Because the effort of
getting rid of it--

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:54.834
if I had the world's most
neat, clean, tidy office,

00:11:54.834 --> 00:11:55.750
that would be amazing.

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:59.340
But the effort of
actually tidying my office

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:01.020
is unbelievably hard.

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:03.290
It's much better just to,
like, put it all in a box

00:12:03.290 --> 00:12:03.870
and just leave it there.

00:12:03.870 --> 00:12:05.020
It's not hurting anyone.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:06.040
It's not in the way.

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:08.600
If it starts to get in the
way or if it starts smelling

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:12.022
or I really need that box
for something else, sure,

00:12:12.022 --> 00:12:12.730
I'll [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:15.300
But it's the same
with your genome.

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:17.580
Evolution is not this
perfect winnowing

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:19.610
engine that gets rid of
everything all the time

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:20.842
it doesn't need.

00:12:20.842 --> 00:12:22.550
And I'm kind of sorry
to break it to you,

00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:26.616
but you are not the
pinnacle of our species.

00:12:26.616 --> 00:12:28.240
I mean, even though
you work at Google.

00:12:28.240 --> 00:12:29.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:29.560 --> 00:12:31.320
Sorry, guys.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:34.660
You are not the bestest, most
fittest example of humanity--

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:35.955
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:35.955 --> 00:12:37.100
--that could possibly be.

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:40.640
Evolution is a constant process.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:41.670
So it's not perfect.

00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:45.650
And we keep stuff in our genomes
that, you know, is just there.

00:12:45.650 --> 00:12:47.150
It's not doing us any harm.

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:48.540
It's just there.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:52.170
So I'm going to focus on
some things in our genomes,

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:53.124
the control switches.

00:12:53.124 --> 00:12:55.040
Because there are some
quite nice stories here

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:57.799
that I cover in a couple
of chapters of the book.

00:12:57.799 --> 00:12:59.840
Now the control switches
I'm going to talk about,

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:02.510
these are the things that
turn our genes on and off

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:05.010
in the right time and
in the right place

00:13:05.010 --> 00:13:06.730
to make the tissues of our body.

00:13:06.730 --> 00:13:07.780
And this is important.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:12.990
Because as I said, all the cells
in your body have the same DNA.

00:13:12.990 --> 00:13:16.510
They all have the same
instruction manual.

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:18.340
But the cells of your
body are different.

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:21.490
You have 200 more than-- way
more than 200 different types

00:13:21.490 --> 00:13:22.390
of cells.

00:13:22.390 --> 00:13:24.950
You know, hair cells, skin
cells, fat cells, liver cells,

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:27.930
kidney cells, all
these kind of things.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:30.890
But you have the same
instruction manual.

00:13:30.890 --> 00:13:32.740
So it obviously
figures that you have

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:37.290
to use your genes in different
ways, different types of cells,

00:13:37.290 --> 00:13:38.400
to get the right outcome.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:39.774
It's the same
thing as, you know,

00:13:39.774 --> 00:13:41.970
if you're making a
glamorous dinner party,

00:13:41.970 --> 00:13:44.390
you'll want glamorous
dinner party recipes.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:46.200
Whereas if you
make a kid's party,

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:49.062
you want kind of a
kid's party recipes.

00:13:49.062 --> 00:13:50.020
So this is the problem.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:52.270
All our cells are not the same.

00:13:52.270 --> 00:13:55.570
And this goes back right to the
very, very beginning of life.

00:13:55.570 --> 00:13:58.660
You start life as
one single cell,

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:01.690
a fertilized egg when mommy
and daddy love each other very

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:02.630
much.

00:14:02.630 --> 00:14:03.650
And you grow.

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:06.170
You grow into two cells,
four cells, eight cells,

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:07.524
a little football of cells.

00:14:07.524 --> 00:14:08.940
You become a sort
of little bubble

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:11.310
of cells with a blob
in the middle of it

00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:13.340
that is going to be you.

00:14:13.340 --> 00:14:17.070
And those cells are the
stem cells that make a baby,

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:20.050
and they have to specialize,
they have to make decisions.

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:22.340
They have to go, are you
going to be head or tail?

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:24.140
Are you going to
be brain or skin?

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:26.045
Are you going to be
inside or outside?

00:14:26.045 --> 00:14:28.440
Are you going to
be gut or liver?

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.836
All the way down to the
really finessed decisions.

00:14:30.836 --> 00:14:32.835
Are you going to be that
bit of your fingernail,

00:14:32.835 --> 00:14:35.440
or that bit of your fingernail?

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:37.940
And all of this is
determined by genes

00:14:37.940 --> 00:14:42.450
turning on and off at the right
time and in the right place.

00:14:42.450 --> 00:14:43.980
So how does that work?

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:46.160
Well, you can think
of this is a bit

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:50.100
like a kind of a genetic
switch, a control switch.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:52.870
So here's our
representation of a gene,

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:54.510
the blue thing with the arrow.

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:56.200
People always draw
genes like this.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:57.050
It's a gene.

00:14:57.050 --> 00:14:58.270
It gets read that way.

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:00.030
That's why we draw
them like that.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:04.570
The little purple thing near the
beginning of the arrow, that's

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:06.480
something called a promoter.

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:08.740
Now all genes have a
promoter at the start.

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:11.500
This is the thing that
says, here's the gene.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:15.380
We start reading it
here in that direction.

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:19.980
Now just having a promoter is
not enough to turn a gene on.

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:24.490
You need a molecule, a
protein, a transcription factor

00:15:24.490 --> 00:15:27.381
to come and sit on
that and say, OK.

00:15:27.381 --> 00:15:27.880
We're here.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:29.130
This is the start of the gene.

00:15:29.130 --> 00:15:31.310
We're going to do
something here.

00:15:31.310 --> 00:15:34.599
But that's still not
enough to turn a gene on.

00:15:34.599 --> 00:15:36.140
So what you have is
a control switch.

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:38.660
That's the little
green thing there.

00:15:38.660 --> 00:15:41.220
And you have other
molecules, depending

00:15:41.220 --> 00:15:44.650
on the type of cell that it
is, that sit on those and say,

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:45.150
right.

00:15:45.150 --> 00:15:49.010
We're going to turn this
gene on here in our cells.

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:50.660
And in other sorts
of cells, they'll

00:15:50.660 --> 00:15:52.960
have a different suite of
these factors that turn genes

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.140
on in different places.

00:15:56.140 --> 00:15:58.950
And ta-da!

00:15:58.950 --> 00:16:03.020
That is enough to
get a gene going.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:05.530
Now obviously that's
just one thing.

00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:08.350
So that's only going to turn
that gene on in the place where

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:10.180
the green thing is happening.

00:16:10.180 --> 00:16:11.480
Does this all make sense?

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:12.080
Yeah?

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.380
Good.

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.310
So of course, if you
want to turn genes on

00:16:15.310 --> 00:16:18.540
in, say, different tissues,
if you need the same gene

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:23.610
to be switched on in the brain,
in the liver, in the kidneys,

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:26.690
in the lungs, but
not anywhere else,

00:16:26.690 --> 00:16:29.770
you need a little
bank of switches

00:16:29.770 --> 00:16:31.580
that all respond to
different factors that

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:36.200
are there in that tissue
at the right time.

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:39.840
So that's a really--
that's about kind of a year

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.510
and a half's worth of a genetics
and molecular biology course

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:43.010
there, guys.

00:16:43.010 --> 00:16:45.020
So well done.

00:16:45.020 --> 00:16:47.720
And now we get to the fun stuff.

00:16:47.720 --> 00:16:49.840
This is Ernest Hemingway.

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:52.507
I love Ernest Hemingway
for many, many reasons,

00:16:52.507 --> 00:16:54.840
mainly because God, that guy
could write a sentence that

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:56.390
punched you in the face.

00:16:56.390 --> 00:16:59.350
But Ernest Hemingway also
liked several things.

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:01.830
So things liked by
Ernest Hemingway,

00:17:01.830 --> 00:17:04.444
I have done a Venn diagram.

00:17:04.444 --> 00:17:06.569
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:06.569 --> 00:17:09.649
Ernest Hemingway likes fighting.

00:17:09.649 --> 00:17:11.690
We know from books like
"Death in the Afternoon,"

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:13.310
he likes fighting.

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:16.795
He also liked fishing, mating--

00:17:16.795 --> 00:17:17.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:20.077
--and all these
things come together--

00:17:20.077 --> 00:17:22.369
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:22.369 --> 00:17:24.180
--in cats.

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:26.599
I knew I'd get back
there in the end.

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:28.670
And specifically, these cats.

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:31.075
Now this is a
polydactyl cat, like I

00:17:31.075 --> 00:17:32.200
mentioned at the beginning.

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:33.510
It has multiple toes.

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:36.030
You can see it's the
thumb there, bizarre,

00:17:36.030 --> 00:17:38.510
three-claw thing.

00:17:38.510 --> 00:17:40.620
So this is a polydactyl cat.

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:43.250
And Ernest Hemingway
had loads of these cats

00:17:43.250 --> 00:17:45.810
on his estate down in Florida,
down in the Florida Keys.

00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:50.065
And the story goes that he was
given one cat called Snowball

00:17:50.065 --> 00:17:52.650
or possibly Snowflake--
the legend is

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:56.490
a bit uncertain-- by
an old ship captain.

00:17:56.490 --> 00:17:58.420
Gave him a six-toed cat.

00:17:58.420 --> 00:18:00.300
And Hemingway kind of
liked them because he

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:03.710
likes the sea and sea
captains, so he kept it.

00:18:03.710 --> 00:18:06.950
And the story's about
why so many of the ships

00:18:06.950 --> 00:18:09.610
had six-toed cats,
because they're

00:18:09.610 --> 00:18:12.260
very popular all down the
eastern seaboard of the US.

00:18:12.260 --> 00:18:15.724
Loads and loads of the
cats have six toes.

00:18:15.724 --> 00:18:17.140
There's an idea
that maybe they're

00:18:17.140 --> 00:18:19.230
better at catching mice.

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:21.780
You know, you've got kind
of big, extra paws, toes.

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:23.970
You can get them.

00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:24.903
Important on a ship.

00:18:24.903 --> 00:18:25.402
Useful.

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:30.540
If the ship's kind of
rocking about a lot and you

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:33.020
have a prehensile
thumb, you could

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:35.452
grab onto a rope or
something like that.

00:18:35.452 --> 00:18:36.785
You just imagine this cat like--

00:18:36.785 --> 00:18:38.240
[MEOW]

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:42.670
--hanging onto the rigging,
that kind of thing.

00:18:42.670 --> 00:18:45.440
There are many reasons
why cats with six toes

00:18:45.440 --> 00:18:47.670
may be useful on board ships.

00:18:47.670 --> 00:18:50.180
The main reason, I think,
is probably this one.

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:52.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:52.610 --> 00:18:55.340
Because, like, what's more
lucky than a cat with five toes,

00:18:55.340 --> 00:18:57.510
right?

00:18:57.510 --> 00:18:59.320
So let's look in a
little bit of depth

00:18:59.320 --> 00:19:02.520
at the switches
that are responsible

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:07.180
for this particular phenomenon.

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:11.150
So this, this is the bit
of proper genetics here.

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:14.290
This is the part of
the cat genome and also

00:19:14.290 --> 00:19:18.390
the human genome that is
responsible for building toes.

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:20.250
I mean, not specifically
building toes.

00:19:20.250 --> 00:19:23.550
There isn't a toe
gene as discussed.

00:19:23.550 --> 00:19:26.550
But there is a molecule, and
it's called sonic hedgehog.

00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:29.210
Yes, after the
cartoon character.

00:19:29.210 --> 00:19:31.630
That's that sort
of little SHH thing

00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:34.020
where the green
arrow's pointing.

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:36.760
And that is responsible
for basically saying,

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:40.140
let's build some digits here.

00:19:40.140 --> 00:19:42.260
Let's do something here.

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:44.479
Now sonic hedgehog is
used all over the body

00:19:44.479 --> 00:19:45.270
during development.

00:19:45.270 --> 00:19:46.990
It's used to build digits.

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:49.200
It's used to make
decisions in the brain.

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:50.610
It's kind of a
deciding molecule.

00:19:50.610 --> 00:19:53.220
It decides things for cells.

00:19:53.220 --> 00:19:55.110
So it gets turned
on in the brain.

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:57.040
Those are the blue
things called CNS.

00:19:57.040 --> 00:20:00.220
Those are the Central
Nervous System switches.

00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:01.850
It's involved in the
skin and the guts,

00:20:01.850 --> 00:20:02.865
the epithelial linings.

00:20:02.865 --> 00:20:05.260
Those are kind of
the orange switches.

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:08.210
But the one I'm really
interested in is the green one.

00:20:08.210 --> 00:20:11.250
And that is the limb
bud switch which

00:20:11.250 --> 00:20:13.840
turns on sonic hedgehog-- that's
the little blue patch there.

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:17.970
This is like the developing
pore of a mouse in the womb.

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:20.430
It turns on sonic hedgehog in
a little strand at the bottom

00:20:20.430 --> 00:20:23.310
where the fleshy part of
your hand's going to be.

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:25.470
And it says, we're going
to make some fingers.

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:27.680
And these ones are going
to be, like, pinky,

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:30.620
fourth finger, third finger, all
the way through to the thumb.

00:20:30.620 --> 00:20:32.120
It's sort of a
gradient that says,

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:35.010
we're going to do
fingers like this.

00:20:35.010 --> 00:20:36.860
So it's a really
important switch.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:41.830
And obviously when
it's faulty, you

00:20:41.830 --> 00:20:44.430
end up with the
cells in the hand,

00:20:44.430 --> 00:20:47.260
in the developing hand, just
kind of not knowing what to do.

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:50.650
They just start making more
and more toes or thumbs,

00:20:50.650 --> 00:20:53.140
because they're just not
really sure what's going on.

00:20:53.140 --> 00:20:55.730
And it's the same
mutation in cats

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:58.330
and a similar mutation
in polydactyl humans

00:20:58.330 --> 00:21:00.300
with multiple fingers as well.

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:03.040
So these switches are
kind of really important.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:05.610
And obviously, there's
an evolutionary advantage

00:21:05.610 --> 00:21:07.780
to cats having six toes.

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:10.540
Because as I said,
on ships they're

00:21:10.540 --> 00:21:14.160
perhaps better at grabbing on or
just that sailors favored them.

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:14.780
And who knows?

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:18.910
Maybe one day these cats with
thumbs may gain other skills

00:21:18.910 --> 00:21:23.280
and possibly learn to
kill us as we sleep.

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:25.583
And I, for one, welcome
our feline overlords.

00:21:25.583 --> 00:21:26.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:31.110
But there's an interesting
and more important thing here.

00:21:31.110 --> 00:21:36.790
So these switches in the genome
are evolution's playground.

00:21:36.790 --> 00:21:39.710
So we think about evolution
as very small changes.

00:21:39.710 --> 00:21:42.420
You know, we're taught
at school that evolution

00:21:42.420 --> 00:21:44.100
is very, very slow.

00:21:44.100 --> 00:21:45.970
One change, and you
get a small thing.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:49.650
Maybe a tail gets a bit bigger
or a neck gets a bit bigger,

00:21:49.650 --> 00:21:52.330
or you get a bit more
spotty, or something.

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:56.270
Evolution is very
slow and gradual.

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:59.660
But as we've seen,
just one faulty switch

00:21:59.660 --> 00:22:03.410
is the difference between
having five toes and six toes.

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:05.920
So small changes
in these switches

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:08.300
can make really big
changes to organisms.

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:11.340
And I'm going to tell you
about one of these stories now.

00:22:11.340 --> 00:22:13.400
So I'd like you
to meet some fish.

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:15.330
We go from cats to fish.

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:18.320
And these are sticklebacks.

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:22.339
Anyone seen sticklebacks,
gone fishing for sticklebacks?

00:22:22.339 --> 00:22:22.880
They're fish.

00:22:22.880 --> 00:22:24.770
They're spiny.

00:22:24.770 --> 00:22:28.050
So the top ones are
sticklebacks that

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:29.280
live in marine environments.

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:30.890
They live in the sea.

00:22:30.890 --> 00:22:32.800
Now about 10,000
years ago, there

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:35.540
were lots of sticklebacks
like that living in the sea.

00:22:35.540 --> 00:22:37.730
And they would always
swim up the rivers

00:22:37.730 --> 00:22:41.890
to spawn and do whatever
it is sticklebacks do.

00:22:41.890 --> 00:22:44.490
I mean, probably carefully
if you've got those spines.

00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:45.990
I'll tell you.

00:22:45.990 --> 00:22:49.230
So they swim up the streams to
go into fresh water to spawn,

00:22:49.230 --> 00:22:51.860
and then they come
back down to the sea.

00:22:51.860 --> 00:22:53.840
Now a bunch of
sticklebacks came really

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:59.070
unstuck in the last ice age
in that they got upstream,

00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:00.930
and then they got stuck.

00:23:00.930 --> 00:23:03.790
So you separated two
populations of sticklebacks.

00:23:03.790 --> 00:23:07.820
So you've got the ones on the
top that are marine dwellers.

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:11.210
And over the course
of 10,000 years,

