00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:07.220
The other thing I want to
really briefly touch on

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:11.670
before I finish is that I've
drawn a lot of pictures for you

00:31:11.670 --> 00:31:14.724
of the idea of a gene as
this long, straight line.

00:31:14.724 --> 00:31:16.390
I've got a gene, we've
got the switches,

00:31:16.390 --> 00:31:19.320
and things kind of sit on
it, and it does this stuff,

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:21.820
and it's all very linear.

00:31:21.820 --> 00:31:23.770
But as I said right
at the beginning,

00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:29.280
you have two meters of DNA in
every single cell of your body.

00:31:29.280 --> 00:31:31.370
That's two meters
of DNA in something

00:31:31.370 --> 00:31:34.570
that's less than the size
of the head of a pin.

00:31:34.570 --> 00:31:37.330
So biology doesn't
look like these kind

00:31:37.330 --> 00:31:41.000
of nice, neat diagrams.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:42.500
The DNA in your
cells kind of looks

00:31:42.500 --> 00:31:46.070
like this, but much, much
more messy and compact,

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:48.270
and it's wrapped up around
all sorts of proteins

00:31:48.270 --> 00:31:50.470
to keep it packed in there.

00:31:50.470 --> 00:31:52.310
And you're like, wow.

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:55.690
How does anything find
anything in there?

00:31:58.420 --> 00:32:02.600
And the idea is that our
biology is actually not

00:32:02.600 --> 00:32:05.000
as neat and linear
as you might think.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.140
You can see a diagram like the
one on the top and think, OK.

00:32:08.140 --> 00:32:12.210
These factors find these
genes and turn them on.

00:32:12.210 --> 00:32:14.810
Stuff's got to find each
other in this complete mess.

00:32:17.770 --> 00:32:19.909
And sometimes it'll work,
and sometimes it won't.

00:32:19.909 --> 00:32:21.700
And genes will go on
and genes will go off,

00:32:21.700 --> 00:32:23.712
and you have to bring
all this mess together.

00:32:23.712 --> 00:32:25.420
And I touch on it a
lot more in the book,

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:27.730
and I'd really encourage
you to find out a bit more.

00:32:27.730 --> 00:32:31.500
But we are products
of probability.

00:32:31.500 --> 00:32:35.940
This is a stochastic event or
random, I prefer to term it.

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:38.190
Scientists prefer stochastic,
because for some reason,

00:32:38.190 --> 00:32:42.850
just saying, like, life's
kind of random upsets people.

00:32:42.850 --> 00:32:45.640
This is a stochastic process.

00:32:45.640 --> 00:32:48.710
Genes aren't exactly
switched on and off.

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:51.770
They're more like kind of
dials, suggestions, landing

00:32:51.770 --> 00:32:55.590
platforms for the things
that make them work.

00:32:55.590 --> 00:32:58.160
And with that in
mind, I'll tell you

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:01.090
a final story before
I finish, which

00:33:01.090 --> 00:33:02.412
is about the wobbly worms.

00:33:02.412 --> 00:33:04.870
So there's a chap called Ben
Lehner who works in Barcelona.

00:33:04.870 --> 00:33:06.560
And he works with
these tiny organisms.

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:08.810
These are nematode
worms, C. elegans.

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:10.890
They're a millimeter long.

00:33:10.890 --> 00:33:12.370
And loads of
biologists love them

00:33:12.370 --> 00:33:16.590
because they are
completely stereotyped.

00:33:16.590 --> 00:33:18.980
They do exactly the
same thing, same time.

00:33:18.980 --> 00:33:20.690
They have an exact
number of cells.

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:22.840
It's about 1,000 cells.

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:27.840
And they all divide in a
completely programmatic way.

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:31.030
So you can start with one
fertilized nematode worm egg

00:33:31.030 --> 00:33:36.090
cell, and you can watch on cue
as the cells pop into existence

00:33:36.090 --> 00:33:38.410
and divide and specialize.

00:33:38.410 --> 00:33:39.500
And they all have names.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:42.190
Every single cell in
that worm has a name.

00:33:42.190 --> 00:33:44.260
They're called things
like AB1 and stuff

00:33:44.260 --> 00:33:46.600
rather than, like, you
know, Carrie and Doris.

00:33:46.600 --> 00:33:50.010
But every single cell
in that worm has a name.

00:33:50.010 --> 00:33:53.150
And the worms that he uses
are genetically identical.

00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:54.660
They're like super clones.

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:57.560
They're all exactly the same.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:01.940
And so you would assume that if
you damaged a gene or a control

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:05.540
switch or something like
that in one of these worms,

00:34:05.540 --> 00:34:11.190
it would come out with exactly
the same outcome all the time.

00:34:11.190 --> 00:34:14.480
And this is where it
gets weird, because you

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:19.870
have this gene, you
make a mistake in it,

00:34:19.870 --> 00:34:23.100
half of the worms die.

00:34:23.100 --> 00:34:27.310
Now that's weird,
because they've all

00:34:27.310 --> 00:34:32.760
got mistake in that gene, but
only half of them have died.

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:35.900
So that tells you that there's
a whole bunch of buffering

00:34:35.900 --> 00:34:37.730
going on in the genome.

00:34:37.730 --> 00:34:40.790
And you know, like I say,
this is a stochastic event.

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:43.150
This is not a yes/no.

00:34:43.150 --> 00:34:46.880
And it highlights that our genes
are not yes/no, deterministic,

00:34:46.880 --> 00:34:49.690
on/off, make this,
don't make that.

00:34:49.690 --> 00:34:53.389
There's a lot of
randomness in there.

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:56.929
Interestingly, if
you break two genes,

00:34:56.929 --> 00:34:58.130
you can shift the balance.

00:34:58.130 --> 00:35:00.740
You'll end up with
10 alive and 90 dead

00:35:00.740 --> 00:35:02.300
if you look at
100 worms that all

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:04.322
carry this gene [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:04.322 --> 00:35:05.780
And you know, if
you start breaking

00:35:05.780 --> 00:35:09.620
more parts of the system,
you'll end up with all dead.

00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:11.870
Biology is incredibly robust.

00:35:11.870 --> 00:35:15.440
We wouldn't be
alive if it wasn't.

00:35:15.440 --> 00:35:17.940
And the final thought
I will leave you with

00:35:17.940 --> 00:35:21.590
is this, is that the more we
start delving into our genomes,

00:35:21.590 --> 00:35:23.110
the more we
sequence, the more we

00:35:23.110 --> 00:35:24.810
understand-- we're
now at this point

00:35:24.810 --> 00:35:27.320
where we kind of
sequence all the things.

00:35:27.320 --> 00:35:30.520
We're starting to sequence
more and more human genomes.

00:35:30.520 --> 00:35:33.400
And we're discovering
incredible stuff.

00:35:33.400 --> 00:35:36.880
We're discovering the fact
that each one of us is walking

00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:40.600
around with about 30 genetic
faults that should probably

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:44.266
kill us, but they don't.

00:35:44.266 --> 00:35:45.890
Because you've got
all this other stuff

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:49.500
that's going on and
buffering in your genome.

00:35:49.500 --> 00:35:52.260
And that's what keeps us
alive, and that's amazing.

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:53.910
Your genome is amazing.

00:35:53.910 --> 00:35:57.382
I hope you enjoy it, and I
hope you also enjoy my book.

00:35:57.382 --> 00:36:01.200
