00:37:09.220 --> 00:37:11.100
AUDIENCE: How do you
even count the genes?

00:37:11.100 --> 00:37:12.686
How do you know
what isn't a gene,

00:37:12.686 --> 00:37:15.382
[INAUDIBLE] to other genes?

00:37:15.382 --> 00:37:16.840
KAT ARNEY: That's
a great question.

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:18.560
So how do we know
what a gene actually

00:37:18.560 --> 00:37:19.916
looks like in the genome?

00:37:19.916 --> 00:37:22.290
So this is the job of something
called genome annotation.

00:37:22.290 --> 00:37:24.873
And there's all these people at
the Sanger Centre in Cambridge

00:37:24.873 --> 00:37:27.180
and the EMBL and things
like this doing it.

00:37:27.180 --> 00:37:29.040
So remember I said
that there's a promoter

00:37:29.040 --> 00:37:30.350
at the start of a gene?

00:37:30.350 --> 00:37:32.790
That's a really
characteristic DNA sequence

00:37:32.790 --> 00:37:33.780
that you can spot it.

00:37:33.780 --> 00:37:36.690
There's things like--
something called a TATA box.

00:37:36.690 --> 00:37:40.490
And that's a run of T, A,
T, A. That kind of thing.

00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:43.199
So you can spot those.

00:37:43.199 --> 00:37:45.490
I don't want to go too much
into the molecular biology.

00:37:45.490 --> 00:37:48.810
But you get little groups
of three DNA letters

00:37:48.810 --> 00:37:51.190
that make the individual
building blocks of a protein.

00:37:51.190 --> 00:37:53.870
So if you get a long
uninterrupted string of things

00:37:53.870 --> 00:37:57.270
that you know are making
proteins, you kind of go, OK.

00:37:57.270 --> 00:37:58.846
That's probably a gene.

00:37:58.846 --> 00:38:00.720
There are some other
characteristics as well,

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:03.060
but it's-- and that this
is where it gets hard

00:38:03.060 --> 00:38:08.170
because there's been this sort
of arbitrary cutoff for how big

00:38:08.170 --> 00:38:09.427
a gene is.

00:38:09.427 --> 00:38:10.010
So you go, OK.

00:38:10.010 --> 00:38:11.384
It has to be over
a certain size.

00:38:11.384 --> 00:38:14.330
It has to make a protein that's
at least this big to be a gene.

00:38:14.330 --> 00:38:15.420
And now we're
discovering that there's

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:16.920
all these kind of
tiny little genes

00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:18.610
that actually make proteins.

00:38:18.610 --> 00:38:22.700
They're called smORFs,
Small Open Reading Frames.

00:38:22.700 --> 00:38:25.520
And it's just because we didn't
just arbitrarily said, oh,

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:26.800
those can't be genes.

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:28.580
So you know, it's
like a fishing net.

00:38:28.580 --> 00:38:30.730
You only catch
the size of things

00:38:30.730 --> 00:38:32.460
that you think
you're fishing for.

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:36.050
And again, we're saying as
humans, these are genes.

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:38.294
And in fact, there's
a lot probably

00:38:38.294 --> 00:38:40.460
that we don't know that's
doing stuff in the genome.

00:38:40.460 --> 00:38:42.900
So it's an open--
an open question

00:38:42.900 --> 00:38:45.481
about what's actually useful
and doing stuff in the genome.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:49.750
Hi.

00:38:49.750 --> 00:38:52.269
AUDIENCE: So my
understanding is that when

00:38:52.269 --> 00:38:54.268
we're sequencing genomes,
we break everything up

00:38:54.268 --> 00:38:54.976
into little bits.

00:38:54.976 --> 00:38:56.804
And then we count
all the little bits

00:38:56.804 --> 00:38:58.575
and we go, oh, they
probably go together

00:38:58.575 --> 00:38:59.685
in this order as a rough.

00:38:59.685 --> 00:39:02.002
How likely is it that
something will come along

00:39:02.002 --> 00:39:03.960
and we found we've been
doing sequencing wrong?

00:39:03.960 --> 00:39:07.092
Or how statistical are
measurements, I guess,

00:39:07.092 --> 00:39:07.758
is the question.

00:39:07.758 --> 00:39:09.800
KAT ARNEY: Oh, so this
is, how accurate is genome

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:11.924
sequencing if we're just
kind of ripping everything

00:39:11.924 --> 00:39:13.770
up and sticking it
back together again?

00:39:13.770 --> 00:39:14.930
You're looking for overlap.

00:39:14.930 --> 00:39:18.530
I mean, the next
generation sequencing-- so

00:39:18.530 --> 00:39:22.160
when I was first a scientist,
the way we sequenced genomes

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:26.820
was you'd start here and read a
bit, and then you'd start here

00:39:26.820 --> 00:39:28.040
and you'd read a bit further.

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:29.740
So it was really--
you kind of knew what

00:39:29.740 --> 00:39:30.864
you were patching together.

00:39:30.864 --> 00:39:34.750
You looked for really big
overlapping bits of DNA.

00:39:34.750 --> 00:39:36.990
The new generation of
sequencing kind of does take--

00:39:36.990 --> 00:39:37.823
takes everything up.

00:39:37.823 --> 00:39:40.110
It's like taking a book,
ripping it all to pieces,

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:43.370
reading it all at once, and
trying to assemble the words.

00:39:43.370 --> 00:39:46.515
And again, you're looking for
multiple overlapping regions.

00:39:46.515 --> 00:39:50.270
And yeah, it does come down to
how good your algorithms are.

00:39:50.270 --> 00:39:53.150
And this is where the problem
is that so much of the genome

00:39:53.150 --> 00:39:54.650
is repetitive.

00:39:54.650 --> 00:39:56.680
that has been ignored.

00:39:56.680 --> 00:40:00.460
And now people are starting to
talk about the platinum genome.

00:40:00.460 --> 00:40:01.640
I had a lovely analogy.

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:04.280
[INAUDIBLE] [? Bernie ?], who's
one of the big sequencing guys.

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:07.792
He said, you know, for ages
we've drawn this map of Europe

00:40:07.792 --> 00:40:08.750
that's like the genome.

00:40:08.750 --> 00:40:10.420
And everyone's gone, oh, God.

00:40:10.420 --> 00:40:14.280
I don't want to have to
do the fjords, you know?

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:15.720
[GROANING]

00:40:15.720 --> 00:40:16.430
I'll just--

00:40:16.430 --> 00:40:20.440
[MUMBLING] But now we're
having to do the fjords

00:40:20.440 --> 00:40:23.360
because there's probably
interesting stuff in there.

00:40:23.360 --> 00:40:25.170
Or we need to know
what's in there so we

00:40:25.170 --> 00:40:26.253
know it's not interesting.

00:40:33.364 --> 00:40:36.092
AUDIENCE: So given the fact that
we have relatively fewer genes,

00:40:36.092 --> 00:40:40.560
but the total size of the
genome is comparable to--

00:40:40.560 --> 00:40:43.060
and probably in the
larger end, does that

00:40:43.060 --> 00:40:44.960
mean that the average
size of our proteins

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:48.407
is typically bigger than
those of other animals?

00:40:48.407 --> 00:40:49.240
KAT ARNEY: Well, no.

00:40:49.240 --> 00:40:51.620
I mean, we've basically
got mammalian genes.

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:55.210
So you know, there's
a pretty standard set

00:40:55.210 --> 00:41:00.020
of genes and proteins that build
vertebrates, build mammals.

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:03.310
And our genes are broadly
the same as those.

00:41:03.310 --> 00:41:07.200
There's nothing in our genes
that's particular to that.

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:10.480
Then it is in the junk,
in the control stuff,

00:41:10.480 --> 00:41:13.820
and all the other stuff
that is special to us.

00:41:13.820 --> 00:41:18.040
And it's quite an interesting
thing to get your head around.

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:20.880
Because obviously, we
basically share all our genes

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:22.250
with the chimp.

00:41:22.250 --> 00:41:26.620
We are pretty much 99.9% chimp.

00:41:26.620 --> 00:41:28.670
So the difference
between us and a chimp

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:30.950
must be that our
control switches,

00:41:30.950 --> 00:41:35.016
our human controlled switches
in our-- rest of our human DNA,

00:41:35.016 --> 00:41:36.890
whereas a chimp's got
chimp control switches.

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:39.310
So you have primate
genes plus humans

00:41:39.310 --> 00:41:43.400
switches makes human, primate
genes plus chimp switches

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:44.720
makes chimp.

00:41:44.720 --> 00:41:49.384
So the actual-- the suite of
genes is very, very similar,

00:41:49.384 --> 00:41:51.300
but it's all the other
stuff that's different.

00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:56.745
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:56.745 --> 00:41:59.220
So there's been quite a
lot of, like, studying

00:41:59.220 --> 00:42:02.190
the genes of
[INAUDIBLE] and cloning

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:08.625
and [? oil ?] companies that
offer to read genes, DNAs.

00:42:08.625 --> 00:42:11.390
But I was wondering,
like, at this point,

00:42:11.390 --> 00:42:14.140
how far is science will
actually being able to,

00:42:14.140 --> 00:42:18.165
like, later on in the
genetic material as like--

00:42:18.165 --> 00:42:19.540
KAT ARNEY: OK, in
terms of, like,

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:22.947
editing and sort of
design-- is this the design

00:42:22.947 --> 00:42:24.280
of [INAUDIBLE] kind of question.

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:27.370
How close are we to taking that
information, manipulating it.

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:30.396
AUDIENCE: Yeah, like-- or even
like if you get to know your,

00:42:30.396 --> 00:42:32.860
like, genetic material,
is there anything you

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:34.110
can do about it at this point?

00:42:34.110 --> 00:42:34.320
KAT ARNEY: Yeah.

00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:35.212
Sure.

00:42:35.212 --> 00:42:37.880
The answer broadly is no.

00:42:37.880 --> 00:42:40.139
I need to be careful,
because Google own 23 of me,

00:42:40.139 --> 00:42:40.638
don't they?

00:42:40.638 --> 00:42:42.502
[LAUGH]

00:42:42.502 --> 00:42:43.750
MALE SPEAKER: A tiny bit.

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:44.666
KAT ARNEY: A tiny bit.

00:42:44.666 --> 00:42:47.779
So there's lots and
lots of organizations

00:42:47.779 --> 00:42:50.320
that will sequence your genome
or at least look at bits of it

00:42:50.320 --> 00:42:50.920
and say, OK.

00:42:50.920 --> 00:42:54.830
You've got this, which is linked
to this tiny increase in risk

00:42:54.830 --> 00:42:57.079
of x, y, zed.

00:42:57.079 --> 00:42:59.120
There are a few diseases
that we know of-- things

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.649
like cystic fibrosis is
a great example-- that we

00:43:01.649 --> 00:43:02.815
call the Mendelian diseases.

00:43:02.815 --> 00:43:05.460
It's like it's one
gene, one fault in it

00:43:05.460 --> 00:43:07.660
gives you the disease.

00:43:07.660 --> 00:43:09.684
The faulty gene in
cystic fibrosis,

00:43:09.684 --> 00:43:11.350
it makes a protein
that kind of shuffles

00:43:11.350 --> 00:43:13.933
salt in and out of your cells
so you don't make mucus properly

00:43:13.933 --> 00:43:15.850
and all this kind of thing.

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:19.170
Most diseases, things
like Alzheimer's, obesity,

00:43:19.170 --> 00:43:21.429
characteristics like
intelligence, even

00:43:21.429 --> 00:43:23.220
things like hair color,
skin color, weight,

00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:27.520
all sorts of things, many, many,
many genes-- and it's about

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:30.070
variation, things being
dialed up and down.

00:43:30.070 --> 00:43:31.700
And like I showed
you with it, you

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:33.699
know, stuff's just kind
of a bit random as well.

00:43:33.699 --> 00:43:36.930
There's a whole random
element in there.

00:43:36.930 --> 00:43:39.190
And that's what's been
really shocking about doing

00:43:39.190 --> 00:43:42.720
the sequencing studies and
discovering that lots and lots

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:46.590
of people are carrying mutations
that should be manifesting

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:49.055
as a disease, but aren't.

00:43:49.055 --> 00:43:49.930
So this is a problem.

00:43:49.930 --> 00:43:51.910
If you have your
genome sequenced,

00:43:51.910 --> 00:43:55.367
we now don't-- we're
starting to go, well,

00:43:55.367 --> 00:43:57.700
we thought that if you had
this, you would be like that.

00:43:57.700 --> 00:43:59.450
But now it's like,
well, if you have this,

00:43:59.450 --> 00:44:01.220
you might be like that.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:04.900
Might depend on a thousand
other variations in your genome,

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:07.140
and we don't understand
all that interplay.

00:44:07.140 --> 00:44:09.590
So there's a huge-- I would
recommend you read my book--

00:44:09.590 --> 00:44:10.926
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:10.926 --> 00:44:12.550
--because there's a
huge chunk in there

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:15.350
about how people are
trying to unpick this

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:18.090
and trying to understand
how we integrate

00:44:18.090 --> 00:44:20.602
all the information in the
genome, not just one gene.

00:44:20.602 --> 00:44:22.810
And this is where it comes
on to the sort of designer

00:44:22.810 --> 00:44:25.094
baby genetic
manipulation question.

00:44:25.094 --> 00:44:27.010
Because you know, there's
all these techniques

00:44:27.010 --> 00:44:29.030
you might read about the
papers called CRISPR and things

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:31.050
like that where you
can cut up bits of DNA

00:44:31.050 --> 00:44:34.202
and manipulate them
and chop stuff around.

00:44:34.202 --> 00:44:37.470
For some characteristics,
for maybe these one gene,

00:44:37.470 --> 00:44:39.070
one disease kind
of characteristics,

00:44:39.070 --> 00:44:42.260
I think that could be
incredible technology.

00:44:42.260 --> 00:44:46.000
Real life-changing technology
for families that are affected.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:48.700
Whether you're saying, OK,
can I do a bit of chopping up

00:44:48.700 --> 00:44:51.430
and make a more
intelligent baby,

00:44:51.430 --> 00:44:53.580
there's so much we don't
know about the genetics

00:44:53.580 --> 00:44:55.670
of intelligence,
and the huge chunk

00:44:55.670 --> 00:44:58.547
of environment,
lifestyle, upbringing

00:44:58.547 --> 00:44:59.630
that comes on top of that.

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:03.070
So I think engineering
more complex traits

00:45:03.070 --> 00:45:05.620
is going to be incredibly
hard, and you're probably

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:07.550
better off just having
sex with a clever guy.

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:09.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:12.709
AUDIENCE: In terms of the
nature-nurture argument,

00:45:12.709 --> 00:45:14.917
my understanding of epigenetics,
which is very basic,

00:45:14.917 --> 00:45:20.240
is that you can pass
the grandparents' genes

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:21.620
through to the grandchildren.

00:45:21.620 --> 00:45:24.310
If the grandparents were obese,
that might get passed down.

00:45:24.310 --> 00:45:26.760
Is that something
that is-- where's

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:28.160
that at in terms of science?

00:45:28.160 --> 00:45:31.000
KAT ARNEY: So in terms of
where the silence is with that,

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:32.890
it's a little bit shaky.

00:45:32.890 --> 00:45:36.040
So the idea of, this
is-- epigenetics

00:45:36.040 --> 00:45:41.150
is a very, very misused and
incredibly abused phrase.

00:45:41.150 --> 00:45:44.800
It's so abused, the poor
thing needs therapy.

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:46.710
This is-- epigenetics
is basically

00:45:46.710 --> 00:45:48.840
describing how your genes
are used differently

00:45:48.840 --> 00:45:50.110
in all the cells of your body.

00:45:50.110 --> 00:45:52.990
Like I said, you've got the
same DNA in all your cells.

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:54.830
You need to turn
genes on and off.

00:45:54.830 --> 00:45:56.180
That's epigenetic.

00:45:56.180 --> 00:46:00.040
It's in addition to the
DNA, to the genetic code.

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:03.030
So that's fundamentally
what epigenetics is.

00:46:03.030 --> 00:46:05.700
The kind of stuff that the
papers get very excited about

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:09.360
is the idea of
transgenerational epigenetics,

00:46:09.360 --> 00:46:13.980
that something that happens
in the DNA of a grandparent

00:46:13.980 --> 00:46:16.720
could get passed on to
their egg or sperm cells,

00:46:16.720 --> 00:46:19.500
and then into the
next generation.

00:46:19.500 --> 00:46:21.320
And this isn't
changes in the DNA.

00:46:21.320 --> 00:46:22.970
This isn't mutations in the DNA.

00:46:22.970 --> 00:46:25.050
This is the sort of
information about stuff

00:46:25.050 --> 00:46:26.930
that's happened
in a lifetime that

00:46:26.930 --> 00:46:30.450
has affected how the genes
work that then get passed on

00:46:30.450 --> 00:46:31.540
down the generations.

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:37.610
And in humans, the evidence
for a lot of this is sketchy.

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:40.800
It probably does happen, but not
in the way that people think.

00:46:40.800 --> 00:46:43.500
And there's been a couple
of really exciting papers

00:46:43.500 --> 00:46:46.130
just in the past couple
of months suggesting

00:46:46.130 --> 00:46:48.380
that maybe tiny little
fragments of RNA

00:46:48.380 --> 00:46:51.110
might be responsible for
transmitting this information.

00:46:51.110 --> 00:46:53.246
But it's a very, very new field.

00:46:53.246 --> 00:46:54.620
And actually, when
I went to talk

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:56.990
to all the researchers
I was talking to,

00:46:56.990 --> 00:47:00.020
I asked them, what's cool?

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:01.040
What's interesting?

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:03.460
And then I said last
of all, what's weird?

00:47:03.460 --> 00:47:05.810
You know, what makes
you think evolution,

00:47:05.810 --> 00:47:07.580
go home, you're drunk?

00:47:07.580 --> 00:47:11.040
And so many of them said,
transgenerational epigenetics.

00:47:11.040 --> 00:47:14.020
It's like it's really
the frontier about how

00:47:14.020 --> 00:47:17.390
your lifestyle, things
you do in your lifetime,

00:47:17.390 --> 00:47:19.790
can they get passed on
to the next generation

00:47:19.790 --> 00:47:22.920
and the one after that, and
potentially even further?

00:47:22.920 --> 00:47:25.240
And there's a whole
chapter about it--

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:26.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:27.280
--in the end of my book.

00:47:27.280 --> 00:47:29.350
Read my book.

00:47:29.350 --> 00:47:30.694
MALE SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:30.694 --> 00:47:33.148
AUDIENCE: So this
is [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:33.148 --> 00:47:37.410
How much information about
creating a human is in the DNA

00:47:37.410 --> 00:47:40.480
compared to-- in sort of
[? transient ?] in living

00:47:40.480 --> 00:47:41.304
humans?

00:47:41.304 --> 00:47:45.589
Or if I had just human DNA,
would I need a human egg

00:47:45.589 --> 00:47:46.770
to make a human?

00:47:46.770 --> 00:47:48.803
Or if I had, like,
T-rex DNA, would I

00:47:48.803 --> 00:47:51.022
need a T-rex to make a T-rex?

00:47:51.022 --> 00:47:53.620
KAT ARNEY: That is a
really great question.

00:47:53.620 --> 00:47:55.550
If you had human
DNA and you put it

00:47:55.550 --> 00:48:04.720
into, like, a primate egg or
any-- anything, into anything--

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:09.180
the problem is that life is
a kind of a slippery concept.

00:48:09.180 --> 00:48:11.860
So life is not
just the molecules.

00:48:11.860 --> 00:48:15.530
Life is not just DNA.

00:48:15.530 --> 00:48:19.520
All cells, all living things,
come from existing cells.

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:22.320
So you would definitely
need to take the DNA

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:26.317
and put it into something.

00:48:26.317 --> 00:48:28.400
I mean, this is what Craig
Venter is trying to do,

00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:31.680
and he's doing it with,
like, very simple bacteria.

00:48:31.680 --> 00:48:35.841
Synthesizing DNA, putting
it into a hollow cell.

00:48:35.841 --> 00:48:37.090
And everyone goes, oh, my God.

00:48:37.090 --> 00:48:37.940
He's created life.

00:48:37.940 --> 00:48:38.696
We're playing God.

00:48:38.696 --> 00:48:40.370
It's like, eh.

00:48:40.370 --> 00:48:42.640
He still took some DNA and
put it into, effectively,

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:44.470
a living cell.

00:48:44.470 --> 00:48:48.680
In terms of whether the switches
and stuff would all work,

00:48:48.680 --> 00:48:49.880
some of them probably would.

00:48:49.880 --> 00:48:51.280
Some of them probably wouldn't.

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:53.170
You can take, say,
a human chromosome,

00:48:53.170 --> 00:48:55.400
and you can put it
into mouse cells,

00:48:55.400 --> 00:48:57.120
and it will start working fine.

00:48:57.120 --> 00:48:58.870
And there's a really
interesting model of,

00:48:58.870 --> 00:49:00.820
I think, Down
syndrome that's based

00:49:00.820 --> 00:49:03.690
on putting a human
chromosome into mouse cells.

00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:08.266
So yeah, some of it
would probably work.

00:49:08.266 --> 00:49:10.550
I don't know.

00:49:10.550 --> 00:49:11.166
I've got time.

00:49:11.166 --> 00:49:11.980
I'll write a grant.

00:49:11.980 --> 00:49:12.979
I'll let you know.

00:49:12.979 --> 00:49:13.770
MALE SPEAKER: Good.

