00:51:04.827 --> 00:51:06.230
the gene responsible for that?

00:51:06.230 --> 00:51:08.550
I mean, we've got cystic
fibrosis and sickle

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:09.540
cell and [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:09.540 --> 00:51:13.500
Is it just if you get enough
sample sizes [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:13.500 --> 00:51:15.945
with it and without
it, you can find it?

00:51:15.945 --> 00:51:18.054
Or some diseases, you
find them [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:18.054 --> 00:51:18.720
KAT ARNEY: Yeah.

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:21.975
So some of the--
a lot of the genes

00:51:21.975 --> 00:51:23.600
that we've known
about for a long time,

00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:27.170
they were really done the hard
way by tracking pedigrees.

00:51:27.170 --> 00:51:30.090
But it's still the same about
taking sections of people's DNA

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:31.424
and reading it and comparing.

00:51:31.424 --> 00:51:33.340
And there's sort of
various mapping techniques

00:51:33.340 --> 00:51:34.380
that you can do.

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:35.870
So all through
the '80s and '90s,

00:51:35.870 --> 00:51:38.810
people were sort of
homing in on regions

00:51:38.810 --> 00:51:41.630
by looking for regions that
were similar between people

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:44.450
and regions that were
different, and going, OK.

00:51:44.450 --> 00:51:45.890
All these people
with this disease

00:51:45.890 --> 00:51:47.700
have broadly this area
that's all similar,

00:51:47.700 --> 00:51:48.990
so it's probably in there.

00:51:48.990 --> 00:51:50.948
And it took years and
years and years and years

00:51:50.948 --> 00:51:51.905
and years and years.

00:51:51.905 --> 00:51:54.030
And then with the sequencing
revolution, all you do

00:51:54.030 --> 00:51:55.405
is you take someone
who's got it,

00:51:55.405 --> 00:51:58.080
takes someone who hasn't, or a
bunch of people who've got it

00:51:58.080 --> 00:51:59.360
and a bunch of people
who haven't, and sequence

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:01.930
them enough, and you'll
probably find some differences.

00:52:01.930 --> 00:52:04.630
And then because of what we
know about what the genome looks

00:52:04.630 --> 00:52:06.140
like, we have quite a good map.

00:52:06.140 --> 00:52:07.320
You can go, OK.

00:52:07.320 --> 00:52:08.970
If this is a syndrome
that's involved

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:11.040
in the shape of the
face, perhaps there's

00:52:11.040 --> 00:52:13.660
a gene that's involved in
cartilage growth or something

00:52:13.660 --> 00:52:14.160
like that.

00:52:14.160 --> 00:52:17.270
So you can make some
pretty sensible deductions.

00:52:17.270 --> 00:52:18.910
What gets more
challenging is when

00:52:18.910 --> 00:52:20.860
you're looking for the
more subtle variations.

00:52:20.860 --> 00:52:22.850
So I work for
Cancer Research UK,

00:52:22.850 --> 00:52:25.070
and we do a lot of these
studies on cancer risk.

00:52:25.070 --> 00:52:27.710
And you have to take tens
of thousands of people

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:30.090
and look for these tiny
variations between them,

00:52:30.090 --> 00:52:34.090
and take 40,000 people
with cancer, 40,000 people

00:52:34.090 --> 00:52:37.230
without cancer-- and it's got
to be the same type of cancer--

00:52:37.230 --> 00:52:41.280
and say, OK, broadly, what
marries up between having

00:52:41.280 --> 00:52:42.390
it and not having it?

00:52:42.390 --> 00:52:46.920
And it's like--
it's a risk thing.

00:52:46.920 --> 00:52:50.490
So it's starting to get very
hard to find these variations

00:52:50.490 --> 00:52:51.430
and to find new genes.

00:52:51.430 --> 00:52:54.150
And people are doing bigger
and bigger and bigger studies

00:52:54.150 --> 00:52:55.810
and finding less
and less and less.

00:52:55.810 --> 00:53:00.070
And I think that's
probably limited benefit

00:53:00.070 --> 00:53:01.890
to be found from
keeping pursuing

00:53:01.890 --> 00:53:04.198
those kinds of
studies, personally.

00:53:04.198 --> 00:53:05.906
MALE SPEAKER: Well,
we'll leave it there.

00:53:05.906 --> 00:53:07.614
Please join me in
